<div id="review_3291014513" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3291014513" />
    <a title="jessica" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10171516-jessica"><img alt="jessica" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509983330p2/10171516.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3291014513?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="jessica" class="user" itemprop="url" name="jessica" href="/user/show/10171516-jessica">jessica</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781503939325" href="/book/show/29904278-from-sand-and-ash">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3291014513" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3655099052352404564">yet again, another five star read by amy harmon. at this point, i cant even be surprised by her consistently phenomenal writing - its now become a dependable expectation. <br/><br/>beyond the fantastic narration, lovable characters, and beautiful storytelling, what i love most about this is the setting. italy is often forgotten when it comes to WWII historical fiction and it was such a wonderful experience to read about the place in which i currently live. its given me a much deeper appreciation for the e</span>
  <span id="freeText3655099052352404564" style="display:none">yet again, another five star read by amy harmon. at this point, i cant even be surprised by her consistently phenomenal writing - its now become a dependable expectation. <br /><br />beyond the fantastic narration, lovable characters, and beautiful storytelling, what i love most about this is the setting. italy is often forgotten when it comes to WWII historical fiction and it was such a wonderful experience to read about the place in which i currently live. its given me a much deeper appreciation for the eternal city, its culture and its history. <br /><br />i also admire the hopeful tone of this novel. while so many monstrosities were committed during the war, i love how this focuses on the goodness of humanity - those who were willing to risk their lives and safety for the lives and safety of others. <br /><br />this book belongs on the TBR list of anyone who enjoys WWII historical fiction, italy, sweet childhood romances, and meaningful stories about resilience and sacrifice. <br /><br /><b>↠ <i>5 stars</i></b></span>
  <a data-text-id="3655099052352404564" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
